			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1314">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>It was with sadness that I read Alison Luterman&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/articles/4154">War of Words</a>&rdquo; [April 2008], describing her efforts to teach poetry to schoolchildren. Early on, she mentions that she stopped herself from using &ldquo;military intelligence&rdquo; as an example of an oxymoron. I graduated from a U.S. service academy where, during a single semester, I was required to pass advanced calculus, organic chemistry, quantum mechanics, electrical engineering, and celestial navigation &mdash; in addition to some humanities courses.</p>

<p>What really upset me, however, was Luterman&rsquo;s unabashed confession that she used her position as a teacher to politically indoctrinate children: &ldquo;I told the students that I was sad because George W. Bush had won &mdash; probably <em>stolen </em>&mdash; the election, and a lot of people were going to die as a result.&rdquo;</p>

<p>It should be noted that a large number of educated people have a different view of the legality of President Bush&rsquo;s victory. But the real issue here is how Luterman assumes she has a right to dictate what her students should think.</p>

<p>If Luterman had attended a U.S. service academy, she might have been surprised to learn that lively political debate is common outside the classroom. In class, however, officers and faculty refrain from engaging in political discussion. They understand that it is an abuse of power to force a captive audience to listen to one&rsquo;s personal agenda.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Michael R. Shevock<br>Portsmouth, New Hampshire</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="1315">
								<p><a href="/contributors/alison-luterman"><strong>Alison Luterman</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>Michael R. Shevock is right that &ldquo;military intelligence,&rdquo; isn&rsquo;t an oxymoron, though that was only a thought, which I did not share with the students. As I say later in the essay, I was doing my best to educate myself about the culture of those who serve and their families. I also agree that, in general, teachers shouldn&rsquo;t impose their political views on their students. The incident in which I did make a political statement occurred the Wednesday after the &ldquo;election.&rdquo; I had just heard the news and was in shock and could not hide my tears. From my point of view, the elections of 2000 and 2004 were fraudulent, a bloodless coup d&rsquo;&eacute;tat &mdash; well, bloodless for those lucky enough not to be in Iraq. What would my responsibility as an educator be if I were teaching school during the regime of Hitler or Pinochet or &ldquo;President-for-Life&rdquo; Duvalier?</p>
	</div>


					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
